<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Business hopes rise in north
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 23 CHAMBERS of commerce in Greater Manchester, Lancashire, Yorkshire and
Humberside yesterday reported steady economic improvement for the first
quarter.
Yorkshire and Humberside's 13 chambers said trading had improved beyond the
levels of last summer, reflecting 'a slow but genuine increase in activity'.
The 10 chambers in north-west England said domestic order books had improved
for the first time in three years, with the number of manufacturers
reporting increases outnumbering those reporting a continuing decline.
But the Manchester chamber's economic committee urged caution until there
were clearer signs of improved capacity utilisation. It also stressed that
banks had a crucial role to play in providing working capital as recovery
picks up. Banks have already warned that overdrafts will be harder to get
than in the 1980s.
Improvements in the last two quarters apply to domestic sales and orders, as
well as investment in plant, machinery and buildings. Expectations of
improved turnover and profit - the main measures of confidence - are
strongly up.
Exports are faltering in some markets, although Yorkshire and Humberside
manufacturers are reporting strong quarter-on-quarter improvements.
Between 20 per cent and 25 per cent of businesses have been recruiting,
rather than shedding labour. Up to 40 per cent had continuing difficulties
in finding the right people for posts.
The Yorkshire and Humberside chambers surveyed 1,492 businesses. The
north-west survey, co-ordinated by Manchester chamber's economic committee
and Pieda, the economics consultancy, involved 778 businesses.
Mr David Kern, chief economist at National Westminster Bank, sounded a note
of caution yesterday about the economic recovery by forecasting that
unemployment in London and the south-east would rise 13 per cent in the year
ahead, compared with a national increase of 10 per cent.
</TEXT>
