<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / BBC will survey employee opinion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC is going to conduct its most detailed investigation of what its
staff think of the corporation, their jobs and their management.
One third of the 24,500 staff, including the World Service and BBC
Enterprises, will be chosen at random and be asked to complete a 28-page
questionnaire.
The 100 questions include more than 20 on BBC managers. Staff will be asked
the extent to which managers accomplish high-quality work, take public
responsibility for mistakes and communicate in an open and direct manner.
The questionnaires will be confidential and will be sent directly to
independent consultants for analysis.
The results of what is expected to become an annual test of staff opinions
will be published.
Mr Alaric Mostyn, head of corporate international communications, said the
results would not change basic corporation strategies such as Producer
Choice - the controversial strategy which gives producers the freedom to buy
services from the external market.
The BBC has also commissioned a large survey of public opinion of the
corporation.
</TEXT>
