<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Threat of more rail strikes recedes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE THREAT of further strike action on British Rail receded last night as
Aslef, the train drivers' union, settled its dispute with BR management and
the main rail union, the RMT, agreed to resume talks today.
The RMT will not call a third 24-hour stoppage this week and has told BR it
wants to take part in 'intensive discussions'. BR, welcoming the move,
confirmed fresh talks would be held today in London.
Mr Paul Watkinson, BR's personnel director, said: 'I hope that the RMT's
willingness to reopen the dialogue means they will now demonstrate the sort
of flexibility needed to end this damaging and fruitless dispute.'
Aslef said it had reached a 'satisfactory' position with BR over its
national agreement.
Mr Derrick Fullick, Aslef general secretary, said BR had agreed to honour
all national agreements incorporated in individual contracts of employment,
including transfer and redundancy arrangements in the approach to
privatisation.
Mr Watkinson said of the Aslef settlement: 'This is welcome news for our
passengers and freight customers. Settlement was achieved not by last
Friday's strike, which was damaging and pointless, but by the two sides
working out the best solution for both of them in an atmosphere of mutual
goodwill.'
The RMT has been attempting to get assurances from BR that there will be no
compulsory redundancies and no further use of outside contractors. The union
says there has been a softening in management's position over the past few
days.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said the union was 'going to test
BR's good faith' in the talks. If management wanted a negotiated settlement
'all the elements are there', he said.
</TEXT>
