<PROFILE>_AN-DDTCVABLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930420
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / Pakistan calls off talks with donors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and FARHAN BOKHARI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PAKISTAN last night called off a planned annual meeting with international
aid donors as the country's political crisis prompted a review of economic
policy-making.
The caretaker government appointed on Sunday to replace the dismissed
administration of Mr Nawaz Sharif postponed the talks just hours before a
delegation was due to leave for Paris to meet representatives of donor
organisations, including the World Bank.
Mr Sharif's two-year-old government was sacked by President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan, who also dissolved the national assembly and promised elections within
three months.
The government said the talks were being postponed 'in view of the political
change'.
It said: 'The compulsion of the economic problems that have been inherited
by the caretaker government calls for a full assessment of the present
economic situation and the formulation of an appropriate response to restore
financial balance. This is expected to create a more conducive environment
with the aid-donor community.'
Mr Ishaq Khan has accused Mr Sharif's government of economic mismanagement,
as well as corruption, over-spending and mishandling an extensive
privatisation programme.
But it is not clear what changes, if any, the caretaker government will
make. In the past, frequent changes of government prevented Pakistan from
trying to maintain some continuity in economic policy. The economy in the
year to June is expected to grow by just over 5 per cent in line with
previous years' perfor-mance.
Mr Sharif's government has allowed the budget deficit to grow above its
target of 5 per cent of national output and it is likely to be about 7 per
cent this year.
Mr Sartaj Aziz, Mr Sharif's finance minister, told the FT yesterday that he
expected continuity in policy-making. 'I'm sure the new (caretaker)
government will carry on talking to donors and trying to attract foreign
investors,' he said.
Mr Sharif's dismissal came the day after a televised speech in which he
accused the president of conspiring to overthrow him.
Mr Ishaq Khan's move was the climax to an increasingly acrimonious struggle
between the two men about the appointment of a new army chief, over Mr
Sharif's attempts to secure the leadership of the Pakistan Moslem League,
Pakistan's largest party, and over Mr Sharif's attempt to curb the
president's powers.
Party leaders yesterday started preparing campaigns for elections. Mr
Sharif, who hails from Punjab province, announced he would travel by train
from Islamabad to Lahore, the Punjab capital, stopping along the way to
campaign. The degree of support the dismissed prime minister can command in
his home province is seen as crucial to his political future.
Meanwhile, supporters of Ms Benazir Bhutto, leader of the opposition
Pakistan People's party, said they were delighted at the opportunity to
fight Mr Sharif at the polls.
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
