<HEADLINE>
FT  20 APR 93 / UN flies 350 injured out of Srebrenica: Bosnian Serbs refuse
to extend deadline for disarming Moslem forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, ROBERT MAUTHNER and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH and French helicopters of the United Nations forces yesterday flew
more than 350 seriously wounded and sick people from the besieged town of
Srebrenica in eastern Bosnia. The local Moslem authorities were refusing to
let more civilians be taken out by road although the UN was hopeful of doing
so in a couple of days.
As the second day of air evacuations got under way under a ceasefire plan
agreed by the Bosnian Serb and Moslem commanders, UN peacekeepers in
Srebrenica asked the Bosnian Serb army to allow the Wednesday deadline for
disarming Moslem forces to be extended by 24 hours.
The commander of the Canadian UN battalion deployed in Srebrenica as part of
the ceasefire agreement argued that there was not enough time for the
disarmament orders to be passed down.
However, General Ratko Mladic, the Bosnian Serb commander, said he would
stick to the letter of the agreement he had signed with the Moslem
commander. He also denied an assertion by General Philippe Morillon,
commander of UN troops in Bosnia, that the besieging forces would withdraw
as soon as Srebrenica was demilitarised.
'The agreement says that combat operations are frozen at current lines
around Srebrenica,' he said.
Meanwhile, Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, suggested that a
high-level meeting of the UN Security Council to discuss the Yugoslav
conflict could be convened in Srebrenica. Alternatively, the London
conference which launched the Yugoslav peace process last August could be
reconvened.
In Washington, President Bill Clinton was said to be 'actively considering
more options' to pressure the Bosnian Serbs into accepting the
internationally brokered peace settlement in Bosnia.
Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, yesterday reiterated his call
for a complete economic blockade of Serbia , after cabinet ministers again
rejected early military action.
Following a special cabinet committee meeting, Mr Hurd said continuing Serb
intransigence 'will bring Serbia to economic disaster'. But he did not rule
out air strikes against Serb supply and communication lines or even
supplying arms to the Bosnian Moslems.
He had a smooth reception from Conservative MPs in the Commons, some of whom
had previously expressed impatience with what they considered Britain's too
timid stance.
Hurd wins backing, Page 10
</TEXT>
