<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 93 / Company directors accused of greed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEAD of Britain's largest organisation representing managers has accused
company directors and managers of greed after a survey by the organisation
showed that they received higher average pay increases than their employees
last year.
The survey, to be published today by the Institute of Management, finds that
directors' sal-aries rose 5.5 per cent on average, while managers' pay
increased 4.5 per cent. Directors' increases exceeded 10 per cent in some
sectors.
Mr Roger Young, director-general of the institute, said: 'Directors and to a
lesser extent managers are still receiving rises well over the rate of
inflation, even though up and down the country other employees are being
forced to take pay cuts and pay freezes.
'This situation cannot continue. Directors and senior managers must be seen
to take a lead when it comes to pay restraint if we are to beat this
recession. Employees are being asked to accept pay freezes and cuts - greedy
managers and directors should be prepared to swallow the same medicine.'
The biggest increase, 15.3 per cent, was for directors in chemicals and
allied industries. Other large average rises were 12.4 per cent for
directors in the public sector, 11.6 per cent in distribution and 10.9 per
cent in energy.
This year the government is seeking a 1.5 per cent pay rise limit on workers
in the public sector.
Managers in mechanical engineering and production received an average 9.6
per cent rise, while those in electrical engineering secured 8.2 per cent
and consultants 7.4 per cent.
The institute's survey covers 25,180 individuals in 392 companies employing
more than 2m people.
Details, Page 9
