<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 93 / Italian PM to quit as voters signal support for reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Giuliano Amato, Italy's prime minister, said last night he intended to
resign amid the country's widening corruption scandals, as voters appeared
to signal strong support for electoral reform.
Mr Amato, whose shaky four-party coalition has led Italy through almost 10
months of unprecedented political upheaval, will consult President Oscar
Luigi Scalfaro today. But he indicated he was ready to lead a new
short-lived government.
Asked in a television interview whether he would head the next cabinet, Mr
Amato said: 'It would be completely wrong for me to speak about it when my
government is about to resign. I know my name is being mentioned and I would
be ready to do it for a short while, if necessary.'
Mr Amato, who said earlier that he believed his government had reached its
end, will see the president immediately after polls close in the two-day
series of referendums on Italy's electoral practices.
With a strong turnout, voters appeared to be showing their backing for
electoral reforms and the ending of state funding for political parties. The
referendums on those issues were the first national test of public reaction
to the wave of corruption scandals which has seen the arrest of some of
Italy's leading politicians and businessmen.
Italians have been voting in eight separate referendums, which are also
about abolition of three ministries and reform of the laws on drugs, the
environment and state bank appointments.
Although exit polls will not be available until later today, it is expected
that there will be support for the two main referendums, which concern
changing the electoral system for the senate, the upper house of parliament,
and abolishing state funding for parties.
At 5pm yesterday, 30.7 per cent of the electorate had voted, 8 percentage
points more than at the same stage in the last referendum two years ago.
In an address to Confindustria, the employers' federation, Mr Amato
emphasised that the mandate of the next government would be to push through
electoral reform.
Political observers are divided as to whether Mr Scalfaro will ask Mr Amato
to stay on, leading a government that might be bolstered by the small
Radical party and a few independents, or seek a wider coalition under an
'institutional' figure such as the leader of the chamber of deputies or the
senate.
